I'm a EE (Double E) student. If you're not familiar with the term  that stands for Electrical Engineering even though it's technically Electrical and Computer Engineering. I take the hardest college courses on the planet in order to attain the BSEE degree and stand out from my lesser peers who do CS. Even though my peers in CS think CS is harder  they have no idea the struggle we go through. EE classes are very difficult  involving a lot more work outside the classroom than normal  business  premed  or even CS level classes. Only very intelligent students are able to thrive in a EE environment so obviously  I've taken several EE classes. In fact  I take a lot of EE classes. I'm currently taking 5 EE classes this semester. EE classes involve exams that test your knowledge of the course and beyond in order to prove you deserve a BSEE degree. An A is the highest score  but usually a C or D would curve to an A or B which would translate to satisfactory understanding of the basic topics of a course. I have taken many EE past exams and have scored solid C's and D's on almost all of them. EE exams are very hard but I am very good at taking them. You have to be very smart in order to get a C or D before the curve. I've gotten quite a few B's and C's. The recruiting and internship components of EE simulate a better life experience better than other mundane majors can. The EE degree is a great way to get ahead in life while you're still in college  and it can help with getting internships at National Instruments  Amazon  Apple  Dell  or Microsoft because you can prove to the college that you're smart enough to already be taking the hardest major  also known as Electrical Engineering  shorthand as EE (Double E).

What's up team   This may not be a meme  but it’s equally as important. Recently  a group of UT undergrads created a fundraising campaign named Fuel Our Heroes Austin (Facebook Page: Fuel Our Heroes Austin) that has partnered with The University of Texas’ Dell Medical School’s Emergency Response Fund for COVID-19 Relief **(a tax deductible donation fund)** to provide philanthropic support. These donations will allow Dell Medical to secure additional resources that are needed during this unprecedented time.  As members of the UT and Austin Community  it’s now our turn to give back to the University that has given us so much. To do this  I **challenge** everyone in this FB group to donate just $5 to the fund. With ~45 000 people in this group  $5 a person comes out to **$225 000**.  To help start even more growth  Fuel Our Heroes Austin has started an Instagram challenge called “See a Texas Memory  Send a Texas Memory.” Rules are as follows: Donate $5 to the campaign  post your favorite UT memory  and tag 5 friends and challenge them to do the same. Make sure to also tag and follow [@fuelourheroesATX](https://www.instagram.com/fuelourheroesatx/) on insta.  “What Starts Here Changes the World.” Here is our opportunity to do just that  starting with our own community. Let’s help take care of our healthcare professionals so we can get back to making memories on the Forty Acres.  For more info: [https://www.fuelourheroesatx.org/](https://www.fuelourheroesatx.org/)  Donate here:[https://hornraiser.utexas.edu/project/20868](https://hornraiser.utexas.edu/project/20868)  Hook ‘Em.  (If we reach a whopping total of $250 000 worth of donations  I’ll shave my head and post it here)

To be fair  you have to have a very high IQ to understand the RotMan 2015 Student President Campaign. The humour is extremely subtle  and without a solid grasp of postmodern politics most of the jokes will go over a typical viewer's head. There's also Rohit's nihilistic outlook  which is deftly woven into his characterisation- his personal philosophy draws heavily from Narodnaya Volya literature  for instance. The fans understand this stuff; they have the intellectual capacity to truly appreciate the depths of these jokes  to realise that they're not just funny- they say something deep about LIFE. As a consequence people who dislike Xavier & Rohit truly ARE idiots- of course they wouldn't appreciate  for instance  the humour in Rohit's existential catchphrase "What Starts Here?" which itself is a cryptic reference to Turgenev's Russian epic Fathers and Sons. I'm smirking right now just imagining one of those addlepated simpletons scratching their heads in confusion as Marshall Kistner's genius wit unfolds itself on their computer screens. What fools.. how I pity them. 😂  And yes  by the way  i DO have a RotMan tattoo. And no  you cannot see it. It's for the ladies' eyes only- and even then they have to demonstrate that they're within 5 IQ points of my own (preferably lower) beforehand. Nothin personnel kid 😎

I'm a TAMS student. If you're not familiar with the term  that stands for Texas Academy of Math and Science. I enrolled in highly advanced college classes at the University of North Texas as a high school student in order to earn 60+ hrs of college credit and become a Junior or even Senior by credit upon entering college. TAMS classes are very difficult  involving a lot more work outside the classroom than normal  honors  or even AP level  classes. Only very intelligent students are able to thrive in the TAMS environment  and I've taken several TAMS classes. In fact  I took 72 hours of TAMS classes over the course of 2 short years. TAMS classes involve actual college curriculum that tests your knowledge of the course at the level of a UNT college student. The 8am Biology classes  Bruce Cafeteria fine dining  and let's not forget the great Dr. Eric Gruver seminar sessions taken at TAMS prepare you for the real college experience better than mundane high school curriculums can. The regular UNT students highly admire the TAMS students for their incredible intellect and athletic ability- if you doubt this  just look up "TAMS kids" or "TAMS students" on twitter! Attending the Texas Academy of Math and Science is a great way to get ahead in college possibly even graduating a year or two early  and it can help with college admissions because you can prove to the college that you're smart enough to already be taking early college classes  also known as the Texas Academy of Math and Science  abbreviated as TAMS.

How would you describe the clout of majors at UT? ❓  Hi! Prospective student here  admitted '24 (hook 'em! 🤘). In HS I've been nonchalant about clout 😒 and haven't thought about jobs at all 🚫 (I'm a CAP admit 🤫). I've kept that it's wiser to transfer to a clout major once accepted to COLA. 🧐 And as much as I hate to say it 😔  I consider the clout of majors at any college I'm applying to. 😏 So  how would you describe the desirability of majors from UT? 🤠 I know applying a "clout rating" 🤭 to majors is quite a jackass thing to do 🥴 and that the purpose of college is not to find a job or acquire clout but to become educated. I'm not looking for solely "clout"; 🙄 l want more than just USA News Rankings 😎 (though I would say I can justify wanting to be intellectually challenged since I scored a 1150 on the SAT  which is over-average  as my friends have told me💁‍♂️). I'll admit it  I have a tendency for talking down to people who do not share my same mental agility 🤷‍♀️ (I've been told I could be a great engineer🙇‍♂️). Specifically  I don't like talking to people that much 👩🏻‍🔬 (did I mention I plan on locking myself in the PCL for weekends at a time? 🤓)  I'm not into partying or alcohol  ❌ and I want a major that can show everyone that I have a sharp wit and reserved demeanor  if that makes sense. 🤷‍♂️ UT is by no means a "clout" school 🔥 (looking at you  MIT & Stanford 🙊)  but I'd like to know your ratings. 😤 Throwaway of course! 😂 Ain't no way I'm doing this on my main.

# The Boy Who Cried Internship (2019)  There once was an engineering boy who was bored as he waited for an internship. To amuse himself he took a great breath and sang out  "Internship! Internship! I’ve got an internship!"  His friends came thru to hype the boy up. But when they hopped into the chat  they found no internship. The boy laughed at the sight of their angry faces.  "Don't cry 'internship'  engineering boy " said the friends  "when there's no internship!" They went grumbling back out of the chat.  Later  the boy sang out again  "Internship! Internship! I’ve got an internship!" To his naughty delight  he watched his friends run up the hill to hype him up for his internship.  When the friends saw no internship they sternly said  "Save your excited song for when there is really a job! Don't cry 'internship' when there is NO internship!"  But the boy just grinned and watched them go grumbling out of the chat once more.  Later  he got a REAL internship. Ecstatic  he leaped to his feet and sang out as loudly as he could  "Internship! Internship!"  But his friends thought he was trying to fool them again  and so they didn't come thru.  The next morning  everyone wondered why the engineering boy hadn't been in touch for a minute. They went up to find the boy in class the next day. They found him weeping.  "I really got an internship! I have plans for next summer! I cried out  "Internship!" Why didn't you come hype me up?”  A senior tried to comfort the boy as they sat down.  "We'll celebrate your internship tonight ” he said  putting his arm around the youth  "Nobody believes a liar...even when he is telling the truth!”

.                   Bullying and corporal punishment   Has anyone ever experienced bullying and corporal punishment?  One fellow Longhorn just told me “people who are humble  respectful  and show humility generally earn more repect from other members of their fields.”  No  in sociology  this is “ideal culture” that people embrace. In reality  people practice “real culture.” When I was a 5-10 year old boy  I was innocent  good-natured  and unharmful. Because my grandfatherm  mom  and  aunt had to go working  I had to wander around my neighborhood.  Unfortunately  one old man who hated my grandparents because they used to be richer than him incited other kids to bully me. He himself threw a stone at my head causing a wound whose scar still remains on my forehead. I was too small and lonely  so I could do nothing.  Later  when I went to school  some of my classmate like teasing and bullying me. When I was in 4-5th grades  I could not stand anymore. I learned how to defend myself. I was a small kid  so I could do nothing but throwing stones at them to defend myself. I acted as though I had been a “porcupine” so that they did not dare to bully me. However  when I fight back  they reported to teachers  and administrators that I started the fight first. As a result  the administrators forced to stand by the flagpole in an attemp to humiliate me in front of all students in my school. They even lowered my rank and banned me from a fieldtrip that was award for outstanding students. Despite those punishments and affrons  I was not afraid.  When I was 6th grader in middle schools  I had some teachers who abused corporal punishments on students. My main teacher was a old woman who was from North Vietnam. When I and some of my classmates could not pay monthly tuition on time  the administrator called her to come the office. When she came back to class  she ordered us to go in the front of class. She beat us with her large wooden yardstick. It was really hurt. My teacher did not care her student  the only thing she cared was money.  Beside  one boy who was on the left to me thought I was from another district  so he kept teasing and bullying me. However  I was no longer an idle kid who was easily bullied. Whenever he hit me  I fought back. Then  my teacher tried to punish me and protect him because he was vice principal’s son. Right then  I told 3 of them that if they wanted to punish me  did not hesitate to do.  In the end of 6th grade  I was not dropped out of my middle school  and I never went to school until I got my GED and went to San Antonio College almost 12 years later. During the time  I learned to educate myself  and I became an autodidact who believed and depended nobody but me. In other words  I became my own teacher.   Therefore  people could not apply what they learned from their schools to me. Sometimes  you will become vulnerable victims if you are to innocent and good-hearted.  Hardships and obstacles will make you strong. Your mocking  hatred  and personal attacks toward me just make me stronger and better.   P/s: If you used to think that you had bad professors at UT  you were still fortunate not to have teachers like mine. Above all  you were all more fortunate than I was because you had a chance to go through middle and high schools. I didn’t have that chance  and I lost most of my childhood friends.

I'm an ASE student. If you're not familiar with the term  that stands for Aerospace Engineering. I took the least time picking my major because I just picked what was first alphabetically. I take college courses in order to attain the BS ASE degree and maybe stand out from my peers whose majors I don't know anything about because I don't talk to anyone. ASE classes are very difficult  involving a lot more work outside the classroom than normal  business  premed  or even ME level  classes. Only very intelligent students are able to thrive in a ASE environment  and that environment is not always the actual aerospace building because I have had no aerospace classes in WRW. In fact  I haven't even taken a lot of Aerospace Engineering classes  and this is my fourth semester. Aerospace Engineering involves exams that test on like air and shit or something in order to prove you deserve a BS ASE degree. An A is the highest score  but usually a D or F would be equivalent to an A or B which would translate to satisfactory understanding of the germane topics of a course. I haven't taken many ASE past exams that I shouldn't talk about so I don't get probation like Hau Pham and have not scored solid anything on the exams I haven't taken. ASE exams are very hard but I am mediocre at taking them. You have to be very smart in order to get a D or F before the curve. I've gotten quite literally no D's and F's. The prospects of going to the Cockrell School of Engineering for a graduate degree or working in the defense industry to kill innocent civilians simulate a better life experience better than other majors can. The ASE degree is a great way to do stuff I don't know yet because I am still clueless about my major  and it probably won't help with getting a job at Boeing or Lockheed Martin because I won't be able to prove to the company that I'm smart enough to stay in the hardest major  also known as Aerospace Engineering  abbreviated as ASE.

Printing is not free  but you can pay for it with Bevo Bucks or by putting money on your printing account  but no one knows how to do that. This library is actually open 24 hours every day during finals week. You'll actually find students camping out here haha. But seriously  avoid the top floors past midnight. Many people always ask me how I was able to get into Plan II as a 16 year old who skipped 3 grades of high school. They think I got in because of my scholarly records  but no the key is the interview.  As I sat in the Liberal Arts Dean's office in front of the board of reviewers for my application  the Dean asks me "Why should you be a good candidate for this school?" They seemed bored but I replied "Well I was born a child prodigy  placed 1st in my state spelling bee for three consecutive years  I can speak eight different languages not counting Latin  play four different instruments  I skipped grades 4 through 6  and graduated my high school as valedictorian at the age of 14. I then worked as an intern at both Bernie Sanders campaign  and New York Times." Suddenly the room burst into laughter and many of board instantly started scribbling down "No" near the application check marks. The Dean says "Sorry but you are just not the type we are looking for." But then I said "Excuse me but I wasn't finished... I watch Rick and Morty" The Dean looked at me like an idiot and said "So....?" Then I replied with a smile "And I understand all the references and subtle jokes" An audible gasp let out by the board was so loud the secretary had to come in. You could hear a pin drop and then suddenly all at once the entire board clicked their pens on the "Approved Box" and I was instantly handed a diploma and now I'm teaching advanced physicals there. I guess you can say I'm pretty smart. :)

We talk about renaming RLM to PMA  but why PMA and not AMP instead? Hear me out  fellas:  1. AMP is spelled the same way as amp  short for the unit ampere  a measure of electric current. This further ties the name of the building back to physics  a subject taught inside the building.  2. AMP can be pronounced with one syllable. PMA can at best be shortened to two  but only if you say “pima” or “puma.” OK  the latter might be kind of cool  but it’s easier to just say “amp.” Better to save your breath to cry about your physics midterms.  3. AMP is in alphabetical order. As such  it does not meaningfully reinforce any academic hierarchies as to the relative importance of astronomy  math or physics  at least not in the way PMA might. Only incidentally  if at all.  4. AMP offers ample opportunity for name-based puns about class. “I’m so AMPed to go to lecture today.” “The dropped midterm really AMPlified my chances of passing that course.” And so on. Can you do the same for PMA? Not really. “PMA pants ” I guess.  5. AMP evokes a cooler vibe overall  bringing to mind guitar amplifiers and shit  I dunno. Does that accurately reflect the STEM major experience? Probably not  but a little positive marketing never hurt anyone.  6. Sure  the library in RLM is already the Physics  Math and Astronomy library. But it’s 2018: Books and reading are for liberal arts and fine arts majors (but probably just liberal arts majors in a few years — save the FAL  y’all). And tradition? Leave that to the College Station cult.  7. The namesake of RLM  Robert Lee Moore  was  besides being a racist  a mathematician. Although AMP still includes mathematics in its acronym  it gives it less of an emphasis than PMA does in terms of syllabic stress on the letter M  which would probably piss Mr. Moore off if he were still alive. You can’t be against that.

Overall  being premed is only for the very intelligent and hardworking because it becomes your entire life and you have to be prepared to give up everything else  including a normal sleep schedule. I'm a Studio Art Major. If you're not familiar with the term  it’s because the art building is in the furthest farthest reaches of campus  the nearest buildings are the coffee shop from which we get our fuel for the day  the DKR stadium  and the brand new EER. Both of which loom over our danky  falling-apart little building every day  reminding us that UT will never give us even the scraps it gives the STEM majors or UT football. We take the most intellectually  physically  and emotionally draining classes to get our grubby  calloused hands on that Bachelor of Fine Arts degree. Even though my peers think all of us “art kids” get to go through college just drawing naked people and getting h*gh at co-ops  they have no idea the struggle we go through. Studio art classes are very difficult  involving a lot more work outside the classroom to make up for the fucking around we do IN the 3 hour  twice a week classes we have (which are either 8-11a  or 2-5p). Only very intelligent people can take a single concept  do DEEP research on it  abstract and develop it for anywhere from two weeks to a whole month  and then (sometimes right before it’s due) be able to pull an all nighter or two to materialize it  pouring your blood (@Xacto knives) sweat and tears into it only to come out with something that at first glance looks like it was made by a toddler. Come critique day  it’s not uncommon for the whole classroom to pick you and your hard work apart for up to 45 minutes  pointing out technical and conceptual flaws that you thought you had worked out. Many students cry during  before  or after critiques  mostly because of the aforementioned all nighters we pull sometimes multiple nights in a row. We’re running on nothing but espresso and adrenaline by the time critiques come around. And there’s either the kids who pulled all nighters like you or those who have their lives together and look extremely put together  making you and your dark circles and puffy eyes feel even more bad than you did already. The worst part is  if everyone just praises you and your work and doesn’t ask any questions  if you don’t challenge or move or confuse anyone  then you’ve failed as an artist. Not only that but often we have to travel so far (sometimes in the cold and rain  or worse: on a UT shuttle) with a project in our hands  praying it doesn’t get dropped or you don’t get bumped into and all your hard work gets ruined. There’s a reason we are one of the smallest schools on campus. Your GPA in high school means absolutely nothing if you don’t have a good portfolio  otherwise you don’t get in. Even when you do get in you’re told it’s time to start competing with the big boys  just because you’re a student doesn’t mean you can’t do anything any other artist can do. Being a Studio Art Major is only for the strong  the dedicated  the painfully romantic  the ones willing to spend four or more years for a degree that you dare not utter around adults  as you will only be asked “what are you gonna do with THAT”. If you want to go to grad school  you’re definitely gonna get rejected if you apply immediately after college. One of my teachers applied to Yale six (6!) times before he finally got in. Last semester  my world renowned photo professor told us all very bluntly and plainly  “none of you are even close to being ready for grad school.” In between undergrad and grad school  we all will have to give in to our biggest enemy  commercial “art”  one way or another  just to make ends meet. This is no major to be underestimated. Being a studio art major is a way of life  there aren’t any tests or facts to learn. There is only one fact in this life: you will definitely fail. Multiple times. It is the only way you will learn.

Only very intelligent students are able to thrive in a UGS environment  and I've taken several Undergraduate Studies classes. In fact  I take a lot of Undergraduate Studies classes. Undergraduate classes involve exams that test on participation and effort in order to prove you deserve a BS UGS degree. An A is the highest score  but usually a D or F would be equivalent to an A or B which would translate to satisfactory understanding of the germane topics of a course. I have taken many UGS past exams and have scored solid D's and F's on almost all of them. UGS exams are very hard but I am very good at taking them. You have to be very smart in order to get a D or F before the curve. I've gotten quite a few D's and F's. The prospects of going to the College of Liberal Arts for a graduate degree or working at a fast food chain simulate a better life experience better than other actual majors can. The UGS degree is a great way to remain in college while you're still in college  and it can help with getting a job at McDonald's or Chick-fil-A because you can prove to the company that you're smart enough to stay in the hardest major  also known as Undergraduate Studies  abbreviated as UGS.

Black Mirror  Season 5  Episode 4:  A college student is doing some kind of research involving  virtual reality that lets someone experience anything they want.  After working on that  they get home and look on their phone at  memes. They see one that they think is absolutely hilarious  so  they decide to send it to their friend  expecting them to think  it's also hilarious and they can share a fun experience. Instead   the only respond  "omg me."    This happens again the next day. After spending all day almost  completely alone in class and in the virtual reality laboratory   they come home and look at memes. They see one they really like   and send it to their frien. They expect some kind of input on the  picture  but instead only receive  "same."  This continues for weeks. The main character is extremely lonely   their only human interaction being extremely rare conversation  with their professors. They hope their friends will be there for  them  but they only ever give generic responses. They start  becoming depressed  thinking no one really cares about them   thinking if people cared they could think of more than a few  cliched words. But they have an idea.  They look at all the people who responded with things like   "literally me " "same " "omg same  "totes me  "me " etc  and  invites those people to look at thier research in the laboratory.  Once they are all there  they are hooked up to the virtual  reality machines  and forced to experience all the memes that  they said they were like. Forever. The main character leaves  themalone in the laboratory indefinitely to live out the memes  until they die  because they were willing to let the main  character live out their life alone until they died only ever  receiving meaningless  thoughtless cliched phrases.

To be fair  you have to have a very high IQ to understand Rose Tico. Her purpose in The Last Jedi is extremely subtle  and without a solid grasp of character development most of her scenes will go over a typical viewer's head. There's also Finn's self-centered outlook  which is deftly woven into his characterisation - his personal philosophy draws heavily from his focus on survival after escaping the First Order. The fans understand this stuff; they have the intellectual capacity to truly appreciate the depths of these scenes  to realize that they're not just pointless- they say something deep about LIFE. As a consequence people who dislike The Last Jedi truly ARE idiots- of course they wouldn't appreciate  for instance  the humour in Luke's existencial catchphrase "Impressive... Every word in that sentence was wrong" which itself is a cryptic reference to the learnings of the true nature of the Force by Jedi Master Qui-Gon Jinn. I'm smirking right now just imagining one of those addlepated simpletons scratching their heads in confusion as Rian Johnson's genius unfolds itself on the movie screens. What fools... how I pity them.  And yes by the way  I DO have a BB-8 tattoo. And no  you cannot see it. It's for the ladies' eyes only- And even they have to demonstrate that they're within 5 IQ points of my own (preferably lower) beforehand.

An awkward love story between two students who shared a class this semester  Two people sit together. They are friends. Let's call them A and B. A wants to be more than friends with B  but B does not realize it. A is not sure how to communicate their feelings to B but tries their best anyway. B can tell that A is sending them signals but is not sure how to read them. B has low romantic self-confidence and does not trust that A likes them as more than a friend. So  B brushes off A's advances  much to A's dismay. The two spend some time apart. In that time B develops romantic feelings for A. Deciding that A's signals are romantic in nature after all  B plans to send the same signals back  in hopes to form a romantic relationship with A. However  in that time A has gotten closer to other people  mainly person C  whom B believes is more attractive than them. B sees that and feels that all hope is lost. B stops talking to A to rid themselves of their romantic feelings. A sees this as a rejection of their feelings and by consequence their friendship with B starts to dissolve. As time passes A and B no longer run into each other and cease contact.   What do you think either A or B could have done to save their relationship  or possibly even pursue a romantic one?

I am hurting and need to speak out. I love Plan II  and shaming people for interdisciplinary pursuits is bullying. Being a decent human being (not worthy of receiving hatred) and reading Infinite Jest are not mutually exclusive. I  for instance  received a copy for Christmas my freshman year. I had not asked for it  nor did I know its reputation. My parents had seen that my peers had all gone to private schools or public schools in rich areas  and because we come from a marginally more socioeconomically diverse area and I didn’t have exposure to pretense  it was very important to them that I fit in  so they went ahead and bought me what they had heard was a book hip enough for Plan II. When I realized the implications  I questioned their purchase  but my mother reasoned with me that what Plan II offers is not the label (like McCombs) but value (plus it has opportunities to strengthen my grad school apps). I'm conscious of how lucky and blessed I am to have parents willing to spend $70 to keep me updated with the latest issue of the New Yorker. Yes  there might be some people out there who use Plan II for conspicuous consumption (and that is inconsiderate and a bad trait  but honestly they have the right to major in BHP as they see fit)  but I am also certain that there are other students like me for whom this major is merely functional — who only mention it before we’re asked and for whom this was just the best option after getting rejected from Stanford. So please don't put everybody in the same box. Don't condemn me and make me feel guilty for my major. I'm well aware I come from a more interdisciplinary background than most  but that is not something within my control and I always try not to isolate LAH kids  help when possible and not make fun of Cockrell. Fearing judgement and wanting to hide my lack of job prospects whenever I walk out of the house with my liberal arts degree is unnecessary stress.

We start our journey back in 2008  which is both the beginning of the McConaissance and of the collapse of Texas football.  In 2008  "Tropic Thunder" is released. McConaughey played the minor role of Rick Peck  the agent. His part was small  but McConaughey’s ability to imbue Peck "with the faintest hint of sympathy as he struggled with betraying his best friend and owning a Gulf Stream V ultimately rewrote the ending of the picture  as Peck was originally killed off by the film’s villainous Laotian drug cartel. Instead  Stiller reshot an ending where Peck saves his friend and gets his Gulf Stream. It surely made moviegoers h-h-h-h-h-appy."  2008 was not only a turning point for McConaughey  but also for the Longhorns. Texas started the season ranked 11th  but moved up to 5th before the Red River Shootout against No. 1 Oklahoma. Texas would beat OU 45-35 and take the No. 1 spot in the Polls. Texas went on to win two more games against ranked teams  No. 11 Missouri and No. 7 Oklahoma State. Texas faced off against No. 6 Texas Tech in Lubbock and was up 33-32 with 8 seconds left when "CRABTREE PULLS FREE" happened. Texas lost and has not been ranked No. 1 since.  2009 was a great year for Texas football — they went undefeated and won in a miracle finish against Nebraska in the Big 12 championship game. McConaughey was not in any movies that year  but he decided to transform himself from the star of romantic comedies into a serious actor. I found this quote from him that he said three days before Texas faced Alabama in the national championship game:  "I got to feeling like  for a few years  I was doing something that I liked to do with romantic and action comedies. But believe me  I noticed there were other things that were not coming in. And if they were coming in  it was in an independent form with a much smaller paycheck  and nobody really wanting to get behind them ... But I knew I could say no to the things I'd been doing. In saying no to those things  I knew work was going to dry up for awhile ... Year and a half  still nothing. At two years  all of a sudden  in my opinion  I became a new good idea for some good directors."  Colt McCoy was knocked out of the game in the first quarter and Texas had no chance after that  falling to Alabama 37-21 and giving the Tide their first natty of the Saban era.  2010 was a disaster for the Longhorns  they went 5–7  the first losing season in Austin since 1997. McConaughey spent that year filming three of the movies that would redefine him  "Lincoln Lawyer " "Bernie " and "Killer Joe." These three films shattered all conceived opinions about what McConaughey could do as an actor and established him as a serious an talented actor. Quite a dichotomy from the Longhorns  who began the season ranked 5th  but would finish the season on a 5 game losing streak to power 5 teams.  2011 saw McConaughey win his first acting award since 2005 for his role in Bernie. 2011 would see the Longhorns finished the season 8–5 with a win over Cal in the Holiday bowl. However Texas went 4–5 in conference and once again finished the season unranked.  2012  Texas went 9–4  but still finished the season with 2 straight losses and ended the year unranked. 2012 would also be the last bowl win for Texas  a 31-27 comeback win over Oregon State in the Alamo bowl. Meanwhile McConaughey played the supporting role in "Magic Mike" next to Channing Tatum. This was the first film where McConaughey established himself as a possible Academy Award winner. A film critic wrote of his performance in "Magic Mike":  "A sleeper hit in 2012 for obvious reasons  Magic Mike attempted to explore the underbelly of seedy male erotica that’s supposedly based on star Channing Tatum’s real-life experiences. However  the true toe-tapping treat for audiences was McConaughey’s club owner and former dancer. Equal parts mentor and nefarious shade of the Ghost of Christmas Future  McConaughey acted as Bette Davis to Tatum’s Anne Baxter. As campy as it is gritty  McConaughey playing the older  grosser side of his rom-com bronze statue from only 10 years prior earned a fervent following that even petitioned for Oscar recognition from its most incredulous of devotees."  2013. This was the year Texas fired longtime coach Mack Brown. McConaughey also won his first Oscar. He received the award for best actor for his performance in "Dallas Buyers Club." 2013 also produced one of his most iconic scene. His rhythmic  thumping chant in "Wolf of Wall Street" became famous across the world and is a fixture of Texas home games in DKR. Texas fans think of it as a tribute to their favorite alum and a pump-up chant for the Horns  but what McConaughey is actually doing is sucking up all their players talent so he can use it as an actor. Since McConaughey won that Oscar  Texas has not won more than 6 games in a season.  2014 Texas fans were optimistic because of the hiring of Charlie Strong as HC. He was to breath new life into a stagnant program and bring Texas back into the national spotlight. This was not the case. Charlie Strong was fired last year after a 16-21 record  the worst winning percentage of a HC in Texas history. Some of the lowlights include: - Losing to Kansas for the first time since before WW2 - Back to Back losing seasons for the first time in 30 years - Never beating TCU - Only Texas Coach in history to never win a bowl game  At the same time  Matthew McConaughey has reached the pinnacle of his popularity. Some of his highlights include: -He received an Emmy nomination for his role in "True Detective." - Becoming the face of Lincoln and revived the brand.  He spoke to the Texas Longhorns in 2014 after a 41-7 asskicking by BYU. Rather than rallying the horns  he stole their energy and passion and redirected it into his career. His career tract from 2008–2014 has been dubbed the McConaissance by many. Thus  it is clear that McConaughey has stolen the power of the Texas Longhorns for himself.

Rex turned away anxiously and felt his forehead. Wet. How long had he been sweating? No  Rex  focus. Paul Ryan cleared his throat and spoke  "You will have 1 minute to complete. There is only one question. You may begin in 3 seconds"  Wait  what?  "3"  Only one question? Five minutes?  "2"  How could they possibly fit an entire test in one question?  "1. You may begin."  Those practice tests  the countless tutoring sessions  all made moot by the single question staring him mockingly in the face  "Do you watch Rick and Morty?"  Rex felt the tears welling up in his eyes. It was over just as it had begun. He glanced over at his glorious leader  his skin glowing in the fluorescent lighting. His knowing smile all too obvious. He knew  just as Rex knew  the inevitable result.  "Done!" his leader said  grinning from ear to ear. Rex  defeated  tears streaming down his face now  checked the "No" bubble. Paul looked at the results on both of the papers.  "I'm sorry  Rex " croaked Ryan  "But Trump walled you out by 200 IQ points. He's the smartest man on record."  Trump turned to Rex  who was unable to stop himself from openly sobbing. He formed a shark-tooth grin and spoke   "You're fired"  credit to reddit

At the end my cousin turned to me and proclaimed  "I am the scientist that was once named Rick  but I have now become a pickled cucumber. When I got my first DSLR years ago I had so many questions on how to get the best image out of it. Coming from a camcorder background I was a bit lost and frustrated  I had no idea how to set exposure or focus. I started doing a lot of tests and I started sharing them online. I was finding that my testing and retesting was really starting to pay off because my image quality was getting better and better and people online were starting to notice. I'm definitely not the best out there and I'm definitely not going to claim I know it all but over time I've really found a home on the internet. A lot of people  a lot of people have really found my tutorials and everything very helpful. With all the testing and retesting I've done over the years I've compacted all my knowledge into one place called "The Store" and some of these courses are really detailed and let me allow me to slow down and really explain things in detail  some of these courses are over 3 hours long and my hope is that they'll get you up to speed really quick.
